.PP
Convert binary representation, of an integer, to an Erlang integer.


.RE
.B
\fBcipher_info(Type) -> Result\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Type :: cipher(),\fR
\fB                         Result ::\fR
\fB                             #{key_length := integer(),\fR
\fB                               iv_length := integer(),\fR
\fB                               block_size := integer(),\fR
\fB                               mode := CipherModes,\fR
\fB                               type := undefined | integer(),\fR
\fB                               prop_aead := boolean()},\fR
\fB                         CipherModes ::\fR
\fB                             undefined | cbc_mode | ccm_mode |\fR
\fB                             cfb_mode | ctr_mode | ecb_mode | gcm_mode |\fR
\fB                             ige_mode | ocb_mode | ofb_mode |\fR
\fB                             wrap_mode | xts_mode.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get information about a cipher algorithm.

.PP
Returns a map with information about block size, key length, IV length, aead support and possibly other properties of the cipher algorithm in question.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe ciphers \fIaes_cbc\fR, \fIaes_cfb8\fR, \fIaes_cfb128\fR, \fIaes_ctr\fR, \fIaes_ecb\fR, \fIaes_gcm\fR and \fIaes_ccm\fR has no keylength in the \fIType\fR as opposed to for example \fIaes_128_ctr\fR. They adapt to the length of the key provided in the encrypt and decrypt function. Therefore it is impossible to return a valid keylength in the map. Always use a \fIType\fR with an explicit key length,


.PP
For a list of supported cipher algorithms, see supports(ciphers).


.RE
.B
\fBcompute_key(Type, OthersPublicKey, MyPrivateKey, Params) ->\fR
\fB                     SharedSecret\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Type :: dh | ecdh | eddh | srp,\fR
\fB                         SharedSecret :: binary(),\fR
\fB                         OthersPublicKey ::\fR
\fB                             dh_public() | ecdh_public() | srp_public(),\fR
\fB                         MyPrivateKey ::\fR
\fB                             dh_private() |\fR
\fB                             ecdh_private() |\fR
\fB                             {srp_public(), srp_private()},\fR
\fB                         Params ::\fR
\fB                             dh_params() |\fR
\fB                             ecdh_params() |\fR
\fB                             srp_comp_params().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Compute the shared secret from the private key and the other party's public key.

.PP
See also \fIpublic_key:compute_key/2\fR.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_final(State) -> FinalResult\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          State :: crypto_state(),\fR
\fB                          FinalResult :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Finalize a streaming encryptions or decryptions operation and delivers the final bytes of the final block.

.PP
The data returned from this function may be empty if no padding was enabled in \fIcrypto_init/3\fR or \fIcrypto_init/4\fR.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_get_data(State) -> Result\fR
\fB                         when State :: crypto_state(), Result :: map().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return information about a \fIcrypto_state/0\fR.

.PP
The information returned is a map, which currently contains at least:

size
.RS 2
The number of bytes encrypted or decrypted so far.


.RE

padding_size
.RS 2
After a call to 
\fIcrypto_final/1\fR it contains the number of bytes padded. Otherwise 0.

.RE

padding_type
.RS 2
The type of the padding as provided in the call to 
\fIcrypto_init/3\fR or \fIcrypto_init/4\fR.

.RE

encrypt
.RS 2
Is 
\fItrue\fR if encryption is performed. It is \fIfalse\fR otherwise.

.RE

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_init(Cipher, Key, FlagOrOptions) -> State\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Cipher :: cipher_no_iv(),\fR
\fB                         Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                         FlagOrOptions :: crypto_opts() | boolean(),\fR
\fB                         State :: crypto_state().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Initialize the state for a streaming encryption or decryption operation.

.PP
Equivalent to the call \fIcrypto_init(Cipher, Key, <<>>, FlagOrOptions)\fR. It is intended for ciphers without an IV (nounce).

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_init(Cipher, Key, IV, FlagOrOptions) -> State\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Cipher :: cipher_iv(),\fR
\fB                         Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                         IV :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                         FlagOrOptions :: crypto_opts(),\fR
\fB                         State :: crypto_state().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Initialize the state for a streaming encryptions or decryptions operation.

.PP
The returned state should be used as argument to \fIcrypto_update/2\fR and \fIcrypto_final/1\fR to do the actual encryption or decryption.

.PP
If \fIIV = <<>>\fR, no IV is used. This is intended for ciphers without an IV (nounce). See \fIcrypto_init/3\fR.

.PP
For encryption, set the \fIFlagOrOptions\fR to \fItrue\fR or \fI[{encrypt,true}]\fR. For decryption, set it to \fIfalse\fR or \fI[{encrypt,false}]\fR.

.PP
Padding could be enabled with the option {padding,Padding}. The cryptolib_padding enables \fIpkcs_padding\fR or no padding (\fInone\fR). The paddings \fIzero\fR or \fIrandom\fR fills the last part of the last block with zeroes or random bytes. If the last block is already full, nothing is added.

.PP
In decryption, the cryptolib_padding removes such padding, if present. The otp_padding is not removed - it has to be done elsewhere.

.PP
If padding is \fI{padding,none}\fR or not specified and the total data from all subsequent crypto_updates does not fill the last block fully, that last data is lost. In case of \fI{padding,none}\fR there will be an error in this case. If padding is not specified, the bytes of the unfilled block is silently discarded.

.PP
The actual padding is performed by \fIcrypto_final/1\fR.

.PP
For blocksizes call \fIcipher_info/1\fR.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.

.PP
See examples in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time(Cipher, Key, Data, FlagOrOptions) -> Result\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Cipher :: cipher_no_iv(),\fR
\fB                             Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                             Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                             FlagOrOptions :: crypto_opts() | boolean(),\fR
\fB                             Result :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Do a complete encrypt or decrypt of the full text.

.PP
As \fIcrypto_one_time/5\fR but for ciphers without IVs.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time(Cipher, Key, IV, Data, FlagOrOptions) -> Result\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Cipher :: cipher_iv(),\fR
\fB                             Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                             IV :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                             Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                             FlagOrOptions :: crypto_opts() | boolean(),\fR
\fB                             Result :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Do a complete encrypt or decrypt of the full text.

.PP
Argument \fIData\fR is the text to be encrypted or decrypted.

.PP
For encryption, set the \fIFlagOrOptions\fR to \fItrue\fR. For decryption, set it to \fIfalse\fR. For setting other options, see \fIcrypto_init/4\fR.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.

.PP
See examples in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time_aead(State, IV, InText, AAD) -> Result\fR
\fB                              when\fR
\fB                                  State :: crypto_state(),\fR
\fB                                  IV :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  InText :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  AAD :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  Result ::\fR
\fB                                      EncryptResult | DecryptResult,\fR
\fB                                  EncryptResult :: binary(),\fR
\fB                                  DecryptResult :: binary() | error.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Do a complete encrypt or decrypt with an AEAD cipher of the full text.

.PP
Similar to 'crypto_one_time_aead/7' but uses the handle from 'crypto_one_time_aead_init/4'.

.PP
Appends the tag of the specified 'TagLength' to the end of the encrypted data, when doing encryption. Strips the tag from the end of 'InText' and verifies it when doing decryption.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time_aead(Cipher, Key, IV, InText, AAD,\fR
\fB                           EncFlag :: true) ->\fR
\fB                              Result\fR
\fB                              when\fR
\fB                                  Cipher :: cipher_aead(),\fR
\fB                                  Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  IV :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  InText :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  AAD :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  Result :: EncryptResult,\fR
\fB                                  EncryptResult ::\fR
\fB                                      {OutCryptoText, OutTag},\fR
\fB                                  OutCryptoText :: binary(),\fR
\fB                                  OutTag :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Do a complete encrypt with an AEAD cipher of the full text with the default tag length.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIcrypto_one_time_aead(Cipher, Key, IV, InText, AAD, TagLength, true)\fR where \fITagLength\fR is the default tag length for the given \fICipher\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time_aead(Cipher, Key, IV, InText, AAD, TagOrTagLength,\fR
\fB                           EncFlag) ->\fR
\fB                              Result\fR
\fB                              when\fR
\fB                                  Cipher :: cipher_aead(),\fR
\fB                                  Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  IV :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  InText :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  AAD :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  TagOrTagLength ::\fR
\fB                                      EncryptTagLength | DecryptTag,\fR
\fB                                  EncryptTagLength :: non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                                  DecryptTag :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                  EncFlag :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                                  Result ::\fR
\fB                                      EncryptResult | DecryptResult,\fR
\fB                                  EncryptResult ::\fR
\fB                                      {OutCryptoText, OutTag},\fR
\fB                                  DecryptResult :: OutPlainText | error,\fR
\fB                                  OutCryptoText :: binary(),\fR
\fB                                  OutTag :: binary(),\fR
\fB                                  OutPlainText :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Do a complete encrypt or decrypt with an AEAD cipher of the full text.

.PP
For encryption, set the \fIEncryptFlag\fR to \fItrue\fR and set the \fITagOrTagLength\fR to the wanted size (in bytes) of the tag, that is, the tag length. If the default length is wanted, the \fIcrypto_one_time_aead/6\fR form may be used.

.PP
For decryption, set the \fIEncryptFlag\fR to \fIfalse\fR and put the tag to be checked in the argument \fITagOrTagLength\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThe length of the tag at decryption is not checked by the function. It is the caller's responsibility to ensure that the length of the tag matches the length of the tag used when the data was encrypted. Otherwise the decryption may succeed if the given tag only matches the start of the proper tag.


.PP
Additional Authentication Data (AAD) is plaintext data that will not be encrypted, but will be covered by authenticity protection. It should be provided through the \fIAAD\fR argument, but can be an empty binary as well (\fI<<>>\fR) if not needed. In that case, a plain AE (Authenticated Encryption) is performed instead of AEAD (Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data). This function only supports ciphers that can be used both with and without AAD.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.

.PP
See examples in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_one_time_aead_init(Cipher, Key, TagLength, EncFlag) ->\fR
\fB                                   Result\fR
\fB                                   when\fR
\fB                                       Cipher :: cipher_aead(),\fR
\fB                                       Key :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                                       TagLength :: non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                                       EncFlag :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                                       Result :: crypto_state().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Initializes AEAD cipher.

.PP
Similar to 'crypto_one_time_aead/7' but only does the initialization part, returns a handle that can be used with 'crypto_one_time_aead/4' serveral times.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_update(State, Data) -> Result\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           State :: crypto_state(),\fR
\fB                           Data :: iodata(),\fR
\fB                           Result :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Add data to a streaming encryption or decryption operation.

.PP
If the part is less than a number of full blocks, only the full blocks (possibly none) are encrypted or decrypted and the remaining bytes are saved to the next \fIcrypto_update\fR operation. The \fIState\fR should be created with \fIcrypto_init/3\fR or \fIcrypto_init/4\fR.

.PP
Uses the 3-tuple style for error handling.

.PP
See examples in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBdecapsulate_key(Type, MyPrivKey, EncapSecret) -> Secret\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Type :: kem(),\fR
\fB                             MyPrivKey :: binary(),\fR
\fB                             EncapSecret :: binary(),\fR
\fB                             Secret :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Regenerate shared secret from encapsulated secret and private key.

.PP
Returns a shared secret for encryption/decryption by local party.

.PP
Supported encapsulation methods can be obtained with \fIsupports(kems)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBec_curve(CurveName) -> ExplicitCurve\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      CurveName :: ec_named_curve(),\fR
\fB                      ExplicitCurve :: ec_explicit_curve().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return the defining parameters of a elliptic curve.


.RE
.B
\fBec_curves() -> [EllipticCurve]\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       EllipticCurve ::\fR
\fB                           ec_named_curve() |\fR
\fB                           edwards_curve_dh() |\fR
\fB                           edwards_curve_ed().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return all supported named elliptic curves.


.RE
.B
\fBenable_fips_mode(Enable) -> Result\fR
\fB                          when Enable :: boolean(), Result :: boolean().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: crypto:enable_fips_mode/1 is deprecated; use config parameter fips_mode
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Enable or disable FIPs mode.

.PP
Argument \fIEnable\fR should be \fItrue\fR to enable and \fIfalse\fR to disable FIPS mode. Returns \fItrue\fR if the operation was successful or \fIfalse\fR otherwise.

.PP
Note that to enable FIPS mode successfully, OTP must be built with the configure option \fI--enable-fips\fR, and the underlying libcrypto must also support FIPS.

.PP
See also \fIinfo_fips/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBencapsulate_key(Type, OthersPublicKey) -> {Secret, EncapSecret}\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Type :: kem(),\fR
\fB                             OthersPublicKey :: binary(),\fR
\fB                             Secret :: binary(),\fR
\fB                             EncapSecret :: binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Generate encapsulated shared secret from the other party's public key.

.PP
Returns both a shared secret for encryption/decryption by local party and an encapsulated format of the same secret to be safely sent to the other party. With its private key, the other party can decapsulate the received secret (with \fIdecapsulate_key/3\fR for example) to regenerate the same shared secret.

.PP
Supported encapsulation methods can be obtained with \fIsupports(kems)\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_add(Engine) -> Result\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                        Result :: ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Add the engine to OpenSSL's internal list.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_by_id(EngineId) -> Result\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          EngineId :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                          Result ::\fR
\fB                              {ok, Engine :: engine_ref()} |\fR
\fB                              {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get a reference to an already loaded engine with \fIEngineId\fR. An error tuple is returned if the engine cannot be unloaded.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameter is in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_ctrl_cmd_string(Engine, CmdName, CmdArg) -> Result\fR
\fB                                when\fR
\fB                                    Engine :: term(),\fR
\fB                                    CmdName :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                    CmdArg :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                    Result ::\fR
\fB                                        ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send ctrl commands to an OpenSSL engine.

.PP
This function is the same as calling \fIengine_ctrl_cmd_string/4\fR with \fIOptional\fR set to \fIfalse\fR.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_ctrl_cmd_string(Engine, CmdName, CmdArg, Optional) ->\fR
\fB                                Result\fR
\fB                                when\fR
\fB                                    Engine :: term(),\fR
\fB                                    CmdName :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                    CmdArg :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                    Optional :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                                    Result ::\fR
\fB                                        ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Send ctrl commands to an OpenSSL engine.

.PP
\fIOptional\fR is a boolean argument that can relax the semantics of the function. If set to \fItrue\fR it will only return failure if the ENGINE supported the given command name but failed while executing it, if the ENGINE does not support the command name it will simply return success without doing anything. In this case we assume the user is only supplying commands specific to the given ENGINE so we set this to \fIfalse\fR.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_get_all_methods() -> Result\fR
\fB                                when Result :: [engine_method_type()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return a list of all possible engine methods.

.PP
May raise exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_get_id(Engine) -> EngineId\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                           EngineId :: unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return the ID for the engine, or an empty binary if there is no id set.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_get_name(Engine) -> EngineName\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                             EngineName :: unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Return the name (eg a description) for the engine, or an empty binary if there is no name set.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_list() -> Result\fR
\fB                     when Result :: [EngineId :: unicode:chardata()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
List the id's of all engines in OpenSSL's internal list.

.PP
It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.

.PP
May raise exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case engine functionality is not supported by the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_load(EngineId, PreCmds, PostCmds) -> Result\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         EngineId :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                         PreCmds :: [engine_cmnd()],\fR
\fB                         PostCmds :: [engine_cmnd()],\fR
\fB                         Result ::\fR
\fB                             {ok, Engine :: engine_ref()} |\fR
\fB                             {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Load an OpenSSL engine.

.PP
Loads the OpenSSL engine given by \fIEngineId\fR if it is available and intialize it. Returns \fIok\fR and an engine handle, or if the engine cannot be loaded an error tuple is returned.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_register(Engine, EngineMethods) -> Result\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                             EngineMethods :: [engine_method_type()],\fR
\fB                             Result :: ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Register engine to handle some type of methods, for example engine_method_digests.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_remove(Engine) -> Result\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                           Result :: ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Remove the engine from OpenSSL's internal list.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_unload(Engine) -> Result\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                           Result :: ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Unload an OpenSSL engine.

.PP
Unloads the OpenSSL engine given by \fIEngine\fR. An error tuple is returned if the engine cannot be unloaded.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameter is in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBengine_unregister(Engine, EngineMethods) -> Result\fR
\fB                           when\fR
\fB                               Engine :: engine_ref(),\fR
\fB                               EngineMethods :: [engine_method_type()],\fR
\fB                               Result :: ok | {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Unregister engine so it does not handle some type of methods.

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.


.RE
.B
\fBensure_engine_loaded(EngineId, LibPath) -> Result\fR
\fB                              when\fR
\fB                                  EngineId :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                  LibPath :: unicode:chardata(),\fR
\fB                                  Result ::\fR
\fB                                      {ok, Engine :: engine_ref()} |\fR
\fB                                      {error, Reason :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Load a dynamic engine if not already done.

.PP
Loada the engine given by \fIEngineId\fR and the path to the dynamic library implementing the engine. An error tuple is returned if the engine cannot be loaded.

.PP
This function differs from the normal engine_load in the sense that it also add the engine id to OpenSSL's internal engine list. The difference between the first call and the following is that the first loads the engine with the dynamical engine and the following calls fetch it from the OpenSSL's engine list. All references that is returned are equal.

.PP
Use \fIengine_unload/1\fR function to remove the references. But remember that \fIengine_unload/1\fR just removes the references to the engine and not the tag in OpenSSL's engine list. That has to be done with the \fIengine_remove/1\fR function when needed (just called once, from any of the references you got).

.PP
The function raises a \fIerror:badarg\fR if the parameters are in wrong format. It may also raise the exception \fIerror:notsup\fR in case there is no engine support in the underlying OpenSSL implementation.

.PP
See also the chapter Engine Load in the User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBexor(iodata(), iodata()) -> binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Perform bit-wise XOR (exclusive or) on the data supplied.

.PP
The two byte sequences must be of equal length.


.RE
.B
\fBgenerate_key(Type, Params, PrivKeyIn) -> {PublicKey, PrivKeyOut}\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Type ::\fR
\fB                              dh | ecdh | eddh | eddsa | rsa |\fR
\fB                              mldsa() |\fR
