\fB                        rand_cache_state()};\fR
\fB                   (ExportState :: {crypto_aes, rand_plugin_aes_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                       {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                        rand_plugin_aes_state()};\fR
\fB                   (ExportState ::\fR
\fB                        {crypto_prng1, rand_plugin_prng1_init_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                       {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                        rand_plugin_prng1_init_state()};\fR
\fB                   (State) -> State\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           State ::\fR
\fB                               {rand:alg_handler(crypto),\fR
\fB                                rand_plugin_state()} |\fR
\fB                               {rand:alg_handler(crypto_cache),\fR
\fB                                rand_cache_state()} |\fR
\fB                               {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                                rand_plugin_aes_state()} |\fR
\fB                               {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                                rand_plugin_prng1_state()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a generator for \fIrand\fR with specified algorithm, and save it in the process dictionary.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIrand_seed_alg_s/1\fR but also saves the returned state object (generator) in the process dictionary.  That is, equivalent to \fIrand:seed(rand_seed_alg_s(Alg))\fR.

.PP
See \fIrand:seed/1\fR and \fIrand_seed_alg_s/1\fR. Note the warning about the usage of the process dictionary in \fIrand_seed/0\fR.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
_ = crypto:rand_seed_alg(crypto_cache),
IntegerValue = rand:uniform(42), % 1 .. 42
FloatValue = rand:uniform().     % [0.0, 1.0)

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBrand_seed_alg(Alg :: crypto_aes, Seed :: iodata()) ->\fR
\fB                       {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                        rand_plugin_aes_state()};\fR
\fB                   (Alg :: crypto_prng1, Seed :: iodata()) ->\fR
\fB                       {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                        rand_plugin_prng1_state()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create and seed a generator for \fIrand\fR with specified algorithm, and save it in the process dictionary.

.PP
Equivalent to \fIrand_seed_alg_s/2\fR but also saves the returned state object (generator) in the process dictionary.  That is, equivalent to \fIrand:seed(rand_seed_alg_s(Alg, Seed))\fR.

.PP
See \fIrand:seed/1\fR and \fIrand_seed_alg_s/2\fR. Note the warning about the usage of the process dictionary in \fIrand_seed/0\fR.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
_ = crypto:rand_seed_alg(crypto_aes, "my seed"),
IntegerValue = rand:uniform(42), % 1 .. 42
FloatValue = rand:uniform(),     % [0.0, 1.0)
_ = crypto:rand_seed_alg(crypto_aes, "my seed"),
IntegerValue = rand:uniform(42), % Same values
FloatValue = rand:uniform().     % again

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBrand_seed_alg_s(Alg :: crypto) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto), rand_plugin_state()};\fR
\fB                     (Alg :: crypto_cache) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_cache),\fR
\fB                          rand_cache_state()};\fR
\fB                     (ExportState :: {crypto, rand_plugin_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto), rand_plugin_state()};\fR
\fB                     (ExportState :: {crypto_cache, rand_cache_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_cache),\fR
\fB                          rand_cache_state()};\fR
\fB                     (ExportState ::\fR
\fB                          {crypto_aes, rand_plugin_aes_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                          rand_plugin_aes_state()};\fR
\fB                     (ExportState ::\fR
\fB                          {crypto_prng1, rand_plugin_prng1_init_state()}) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                          rand_plugin_prng1_init_state()};\fR
\fB                     (State) -> State\fR
\fB                         when\fR
\fB                             State ::\fR
\fB                                 {rand:alg_handler(crypto),\fR
\fB                                  rand_plugin_state()} |\fR
\fB                                 {rand:alg_handler(crypto_cache),\fR
\fB                                  rand_cache_state()} |\fR
\fB                                 {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                                  rand_plugin_aes_state()} |\fR
\fB                                 {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                                  rand_plugin_prng1_state()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a generator for \fIrand\fR with specified algorithm.

.PP
Create a state object (generator) for random number generation, which when used by the \fIrand\fR functions produce \fBcryptographically strong\fR random number.

.PP
See \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR and for example \fIrand:uniform_s/2\fR.

.PP
\fBWith \fR\fB\fIAlg = crypto\fR\fR

.PP
The created generator uses OpenSSL's \fIBN_rand_range\fR for uniform integers and floats.

.PP
The generator also implements generating bytes efficiently with OpenSSL's \fIRAND_bytes\fR, just like \fIstrong_rand_bytes/1\fR. See also \fIrand:bytes_s/2\fR.  \fISince OTP @OTP-19882@\fR.

.PP
Because the OpenSSL library is called for every request, this generator has got a very small generator state, but a large call overhead, so for numbers and small numbers of bytes (about 10), it becomes \fIvery\fR slow compared to the default PRNG in the \fIrand\fR module.  This is an unfair comparison because a PRNG is not cryptographically strong.  Still, for a larger numbers of bytes, (about 1 000 or more) this generator is the fastest.

.PP
This function is equivalent to \fIrand_seed_s/0\fR.

.PP
\fBWith \fR\fB\fIAlg = crypto_cache\fR\fR

.PP
The created generator fetches random data with OpenSSL's \fIRAND_bytes\fR, just like \fIstrong_rand_bytes/1\fR, and caches it in the generator's state. Then 56 bit numbers are extracted from the cache, which makes operations in module \fIrand\fR fast on 64 bit machines.

.PP
The generator also implements extracting bytes efficiently. See also \fIrand:bytes_s/2\fR.  \fISince OTP @OTP-19882@\fR.

.PP
Caching random data improves \fIamortized\fR performance a lot so for numbers it becomes less than a factor 2 slower than the default PRNG in the \fIrand\fR module.  For bytes it performs very much like for \fIAlg = crypto\fR above.

.PP
Since this generator caches random data it is a bad idea to copy its state in an attempt to fork into multiple generators. The forked generators will produce the same numbers until their caches are empty, which cannot be regarded as cryptographically strong, and is probably never useful.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
S0 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_cache),
{IntegerValue, S1} = rand:uniform(42, S0), % 1 .. 42
{FloatValue, S2} = rand:uniform(S1).       % [0.0, 1.0)

.fi

.PP
These generators may cause the \fIrand\fR functions using the returned state object to raise the exception \fIerror:low_entropy\fR in case the random generator failed due to lack of secure "randomness".

.PP
The cache size can be changed from its default value using the crypto app's  configuration parameter \fIrand_cache_size\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe state returned from this function cannot be used to get a reproducible random sequence as from the other \fIrand\fR functions, since that would not be cryptographically safe. In fact when random data is cached some numbers may get reproduced, but this is unpredictable. The only supported usage is to generate one distinct random sequence.


.PP
\fBWith argument \fR\fB\fIExportState\fR\fR

.PP
For completeness, this function accepts an \fIExportState\fR from \fIrand:export_seed_s/1\fR used on one of this module's generators. This function can probably only be useful for algorithm \fIcrypto_aes\fR.

.PP
For algorithm \fIcrypto\fR it is not very useful since the produced numbers are as unpredictable for a new generator as for one re-created with this function.

.PP
The same goes for algorithm \fIcrypto_cache\fR, but its exported state may contain cached random numbers which might delay having to call OpenSSL the first time, so there is a possible slight performance gain.

.PP
For algorithm \fIcrypto_aes\fR this function works as described in \fIrand:export_seed_s/1\fR and \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR.

.PP
For algorithm \fIcrypto_prng1\fR this function only works as described in \fIrand:export_seed_s/1\fR and \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR on the initial state after creation (seeding).  After the first random number has been created, the state contains a \fIcrypto_state/0\fR that does not survive a roundtrip through Erlang's external term format.

.PP
\fBWith argument \fR\fB\fIState\fR\fR

.PP
For completeness, this function accepts a \fIState\fR just as \fIrand:seed_s\fR does. Calling this function with a \fIState\fR from one of the algorithms in this module only passes the state through, it is a no-op.


.RE
.B
\fBrand_seed_alg_s(Alg :: crypto_aes, Seed :: iodata()) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_aes),\fR
\fB                          rand_plugin_aes_state()};\fR
\fB                     (Alg :: crypto_prng1, Seed :: iodata()) ->\fR
\fB                         {rand:alg_handler(crypto_prng1),\fR
\fB                          rand_plugin_prng1_state()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create and seed a generator for \fIrand\fR with specified algorithm.

.PP
Create a state object (generator) for random number generation, which when used by the \fIrand\fR functions produce \fBcryptographically unpredictable\fR random numbers, that can be reproduced by re-using the same \fISeed\fR.

.PP
See \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR, and for example \fIrand:uniform_s/2\fR, and compare to \fIrand_seed_alg/1\fR.

.PP
The state objects created by this function has cached data so they use much more memory than the generators in the \fIrand\fR module.

.PP
\fBWith \fR\fB\fIAlg = crypto_aes\fR\fR

.PP
The Xoroshiro928 generator from the \fIrand\fR module is used as a counter. The generator's state is scrambled through AES-256 to create a 58-bit pseudo random value.  This gives a long period (2^928 - 1).

.PP
The result should be statistically completely unpredictable random values, since the scrambling is cryptographically strong and the period is extremely long.  But the generated numbers are not to be regarded as cryptographically strong since there is no re-keying schedule, and since the sequence is repeated for the same seed.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If you need cryptographically strong random numbers use \fIrand_seed_alg_s/1\fR with \fIAlg =:= crypto\fR or \fIAlg =:= crypto_cache\fR.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If you need to be able to repeat the sequence use this function with \fIAlg =:= crypto_aes\fR (or \fIAlg =:= crypto_prng1\fR, below).

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If you do not need the statistical quality of these generators, there are faster generators in the \fIrand\fR module. The \fIamortized\fR speed of this generator is about 3 times slower than the \fIrand\fR module's \fIdefault algorithm\fR.

.RE

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
1> S0 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_aes, "my seed").
2> %% 1..42
   {IntegerValue, S1} = rand:uniform_s(42, S0).
3> %% [0.0, 1.0)
   {FloatValue, S2} = rand:uniform_s(S1).
4> {IntegerValue,FloatValue}.
{9,0.7624867055217882}
5> S3 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_aes, "my seed").
6> %% Same values
   {IntegerValue, S4} = rand:uniform_s(42, S3).
7> %% again
   {FloatValue, S5} = rand:uniform_s(S4).

.fi

.PP
Thanks to the used generator the state object supports the \fIrand:jump/0,1\fR function with distance 2^512.

.PP
Numbers are generated in batches and for speed reasons cached in the generator's state. The cache size can be changed from its default value using the crypto app's  configuration parameter \fIrand_cache_size\fR.

.PP
Generating bytes, see \fIrand:bytes_s/2\fR, is done from the cached numbers, which limits the performance as for generating numbers.  \fIAlg = crypto\fR, is faster, for larger numbers of bytes significantly faster, but cannot be used to reproduce a sequence.  Another alternative is \fIAlg = crypto_prng1\fR that follows here.

.PP
\fBWith \fR\fB\fIAlg = crypto_prng1\fR\fR\fB \fR\fB\fISince OTP @OTP-19882@\fR\fR\fB.\fR

.PP
The created generator uses a stream cipher to encrypt data blocks of zeros, which effectively results in the stream cipher's key stream as binary data. The binary data is cached in the generator's state to achieve good \fIamortized\fR speed.  From the cached data 58 bit numbers are extracted, to facilitate fast operations in the \fIrand\fR module. The cache size can be changed from its default value using the crypto app's  configuration parameter \fIrand_cache_size\fR.

.PP
This generator also implements extracting bytes efficiently through \fIrand:bytes_s/2\fR.

.PP
The key stream from a stream cipher is cryptographically unpredictable, which should result in statistically completely unpredictable random values, but the generated numbers are not to be regarded as cryptographically strong since there is no re-keying schedule, and since the sequence is repeated for the same seed.

.PP
For generating numbers, this generator is about 2 times slower than the default PRNG in the \fIrand\fR module.  For generating bytes, it is significantly faster, for any number of bytes. Compared to \fIAlg = crypto\fR, this generator has much less overhead, so for small numbers of bytes it is much faster.  Break-even is a bit above the cache size, and over that \fIAlg = crypto\fR is faster, but cannot be used to reproduce a sequence.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
1> S0 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_prng1, "my seed").
2> %% 1..42
   {IntegerValue, S1} = rand:uniform_s(42, S0).
3> {Bytes, S2} = rand:bytes_s(7, S1).
4> {IntegerValue,Bytes}.
{20,<<52,185,212,38,248,228,127>>}
5> S3 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_prng1, "my seed").
6> %% Same values
   {IntegerValue, S4} = rand:uniform_s(42, S3).
7> %% again
   {Bytes, S5} = rand:bytes_s(7, S4).

.fi

.PP
The generator's state contains a \fIcrypto_state/0\fR which refers to the same encryption state even when copied, and the generator's state contains \fIcached\fR random data.  It is therefore a bad idea to copy the state in an attempt to fork into multiple generators. The forked generators will produce the same numbers until their caches are empty, and then refill their caches with different sections of the keystream. This is probably never useful.

.PP
The created initial state, however, can be copied and exported, as descrided for \fIrand:export_seed_s/1\fR and \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR, since the \fIcrypto_state/0\fR is not created until the first random value is generated.  An exported subsequent generator state cannot be passed intact through Erlang's external term format, and \fIrand_seed_alg_s/1\fR will fail for an exported state of this generator that is not an initial state.

.PP
\fIrand:jump/1\fR is implemented for this generator, but also only for its initial state.  A jump, for this generator, is implemented by incrementing the cipher's IV to create a distinct keystream. This is not much different from using different seed values, but avoids a call to the hash function that is used when seeding.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
1> Sa0 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_prng1, "my seed").
2> Sb0 = rand:jump(Sa0).
3> {BytesA, Sa1} = rand:bytes_s(7, Sa0).
4> {BytesB, Sb1} = rand:bytes_s(7, Sb0).
5> BytesA.
<<77,185,41,162,118,82,190>>
6> BytesB.
<<160,61,224,29,177,30,68>>
7> SA0 = crypto:rand_seed_alg_s(crypto_prng1, "my seed").
8> SB0 = rand:jump(SA0).
%% Same values again
9> {BytesA, SA1} = rand:bytes_s(7, SA0).
10> {BytesB, SB1} = rand:bytes_s(7, SB0).

.fi

.PP
\fB\fIAlgorithm details\fR\fR

.PP
The \fISeed\fR is hashed with SHA-384 to create a Key and IV for AES-256 that is run in CTR mode over blocks of zero data.


.RE
.B
\fBrand_seed_s() -> {rand:alg_handler(crypto), rand_plugin_state()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a generator for \fIrand\fR.

.PP
Create a state object (generator) for random number generation, which when used by the \fIrand\fR functions produce \fBcryptographically strong\fR random numbers (based on OpenSSL's \fIBN_rand_range\fR function). See \fIrand:seed_s/1\fR, and for example \fIrand:uniform_s/2\fR.

.PP
This generator also implements generating bytes efficiently (based on OpenSSL's \fIRAND_bytes\fR function). See \fIrand:bytes_s/2\fR and \fIstrong_rand_bytes/1\fR. \fISince OTP @OTP-19882@\fR.

.PP
\fB\fIExample\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
S0 = crypto:rand_seed_s(),
{RandomInteger, S1} = rand:uniform_s(1000, S0).

.fi

.PP
May cause the \fIrand\fR functions using this state object to raise the exception \fIerror:low_entropy\fR in case the random generator failed due to lack of secure "randomness".

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe state returned from this function cannot be used to get a reproducible random sequence as from the other \fIrand\fR functions, since that would not be cryptographically safe. The only supported usage is to generate one distinct random sequence.



.RE
.B
\fBrand_uniform(crypto_integer(), crypto_integer()) ->\fR
\fB                      crypto_integer().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: crypto:rand_uniform/2 is deprecated; use strong_rand_range/1 instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Generate a random integer number.

.PP
The interval is \fIFrom =< N < To\fR. Uses the \fIcrypto\fR library pseudo-random number generator. \fITo\fR must be larger than \fIFrom\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis function is deprecated because it originally used the OpenSSL method BN_pseudo_rand_range that was not cryptographically strong and could not run out of entropy. That behaviour changed in OpenSSL and this function cannot be fixed without making it raise \fIerror:low_entropy\fR, which is not backwards compatible. Instead, use \fIstrong_rand_range(To - From) + From\fR Be aware of the possible \fIerror:low_entropy\fR exception.



.RE
.B
\fBsign(Algorithm, DigestType, Msg, Key, Options) -> Signature\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Algorithm :: pk_sign_verify_algs(),\fR
\fB                  DigestType ::\fR
\fB                      rsa_digest_type() |\fR
\fB                      dss_digest_type() |\fR
\fB                      ecdsa_digest_type() |\fR
\fB                      none,\fR
